segments.text: And they had, of course, their own curriculum and something else again.
So I got all kinds of education, but it never fit into my .
So I'd say, actually, probably grade one below the top, which is the .
I'd say .
But you thought he could have helped more.
And he's not political.
He's not...
No, I don't think he would have time to go to any meetings that I know of, because it was odd hours.
Or had to join some sort of...
He might have.
He might have had to join it.
But like you say, you know, you pay the first month's dues and you pay the next, you know, that kind of thing.
Oh, yeah, yeah, no, I'm not making any of that up.
But there wasn't a...
picture of Hindenburg on the wall, or there was a picture of Hitler on the wall, or there was a picture of something.
I'm just trying to gauge your level of...
There might have been a picture of Hindenburg on the wall.
Most families did.
My parents had a picture of Franz Joseph on the wall.
And that influenced the way I feel about things.

Okay, I see the capture, I see the routine shift across North Africa, the big camps, the bigger and bigger holding camps, and your experience with the black GIs, and the difference in treatment between how the British handled you and how the U.S. troops handled you.
I don't get any feeling for searches, endless searches or endless...
Yes.
Yeah, I just didn't...
To me, that's their right.
It's a drag.
We had them.
But I wasn't upset by it too much.
We couldn't figure out what the hell.
They don't throw you somewhere else for that.
They were the constant searches.
And especially toward the end, they searched the camp all the time.
And we had to stay between those two fences.
And the orders were not to touch the fences.
So we had 500 people in this area.
And they guard staring at you and daring you to touch the fence and that kind of thing.
But my way of handling these kind of situations is, you know, I'm in this, I don't make any, I just, to me, that's the time to keep your mouth shut and just do that.
Sure.
So I don't get into any hassles.
It's not my style.
So you went to larger camps and then you were eventually put on
ships and sent to the US, and then put on trains, and then you started to feed into the camp system.
Which I knew nothing about, because I had no idea that there were that many in three or four camps.
Yeah.
And you didn't sidle up to make a close chum that you went through these experiences with?
No.
I always had friends.
But I never, this real closeness that I couldn't live without him, I really never got.
That kind of chumminess.
But lots of friends.
I can go almost anywhere and immediately have somebody I like in response to me.
And we have a gay old time while we're there, whatever we're doing.
But you weren't paired up with somebody or two or three guys you used to meet every now and again in a different camp somewhere and say, oh, I haven't seen you in a long time.
How was life in treating you?
Cold running into him.
It may have happened that way.
But there again, it wasn't that close.
It was just nice to see a familiar face and say hi or hi-o.
Or hi-o, right.
And it may have happened that way.
You can say there was a lot of good comradeship.

that i enjoyed so i was not isolated by my own peers and i had a lot of friends and we had a long barrack you know maybe 40 50 guys in there and you gravitated to your little group make it hey can i get close there right because they like to talk to them better rather than the old grouch down there right upper bunk or lower bunk
I believe in the first camp, we only had one .
There was no one directly from Schweitzer's head.
My unit, in fact, I think, was mentioned.
I got thrown into the Schwab's and the Saxon's.
I came from Prussia .
So I was always in a different environment.
There was no one from my hometown.
That might have made a difference, but I didn't.
I was lucky to be accepted because the Prussians, even in Germany, are not that popular because they're a little more uptight.
more severe climate than the West Germans.
And the Southern Germans are much more gregarious.
The Schwaben, they have their dialect.
And the Saxons have their dialect like the Southern guys here.
Or in the old days, Arkes and Oakies.
Yes.
And so to be accepted in these more gregarious was due to my
own gregariousness, I think, and not be an outcast.
I was not made an outcast.
No, no, I never imagined that you would have been an outcast.
I think that, if anything, you're isolating yourself.
I don't think that they were isolating you.
Did you find yourself a minority, being Catholic, in a Protestant area?
It seemed like it was always 50.
It was always Catholicism.
It was always pretty much 46.
But you didn't feel any animosity because of being Catholic?
No religious strife that I can think of.
Did you expect, even after you were captured, that Germany was likely to win the war?

Did you think it was going to be, well, you know, when you were first captured, was there a sense that I have to wait it out until... Well, I thought they had something, they had a plan of, you know, after all, they're going to be, call themselves field marshals and give themselves titles, and I thought they knew what they were doing, but...
They had some kind of an overall plan.
Did you have any sense of time of how long you were likely to be in the camps, or did you just level out mentally and not think about the future?
Yeah, I probably had, having had quite a bit of history in school, I didn't worry about the length of these things because we had as long in history as long wars before.
And, you know, we had a four-year war, and WWI, and a three-year war, and a seven-year war that was a hundred-year war.
So I was quite concerned.
And by that time, I really, that was one of the reasons probably that contributed to my escape.
I really had given up on any time, right, on any, in my lifetime.
You know, because a hundred years, you got, you know,
So I just thought, I'll just do whatever I have to do.
I have to manufacture cigarette cases.
And schnitzel, that's called schnitzel.
I saw it in a book the other day.
It was quite an art in those days.
Not that I had taken it in school or anything, but all the churches had these wood carvings that were just
literally every wall, everything full of wood carvings that I had seen, not necessarily done.
So when I had the time and somebody, I could get a piece of wood and a knife,
I would do something, because I'd seen so much around me.
I was surrounded by this kind of artwork.
Could you easily get knives, or was there a concern that these would be used as weapons?
They were very easy to find.
They were short knives.
And in the beginning, for most of the time, we had almost an understanding between the guards
And the prisoners, there was nothing we could do.
I mean, come on, where are we going to go?
That type of thing.
Miles from home.
Yeah.
And the realistic approach, we're not going to try this blowing up of railroad things.
It wouldn't have made a damn bit of difference.
It might make a good story, and then
But not where we were.
And where would you blow up?
The desert?
And they couldn't care less.
And you got a few letters from these two girls.
while you were in the camp, were those about the only people who wrote, or were there other people as well?
Oh, other people as well.
I probably kept trying to keep in touch.
I was a fairly good writer in those days, I mean, active, and tried to keep my friends, I wanted to keep my friends in touch.
But I don't really, per se, recall them except those two girls that I wrote to, Maria, and I think if I wrote to any third ones.
But I used to, I would meet girls skiing, like I'd go skiing by myself, and you'd meet these local girls, like in the Riesentuberg, in the Czechoslovakian border.
I would meet some girls that live nearby, come skiing, and stops right next to me.
So you'd meet all kinds of girls, and sometimes you'd ask them for their name and address, and I'd write to you, and things like that.
So I had a lot of contacts.
And by that time, like I say, most of my male friends had gone.
I was one of the last ones to leave the, to enter the services.
They had already gone.
And I will say a little episode.
I remember after they had to, it's in there when the law, there was a law passed, the expulsion of the Jewish people.
I didn't know there was a law passed for it.
It's right in here.
The year after, or very shortly thereafter, I went back to the recently working.
It's in here.
There was a law passed, you know, and I went back.
I said, I was skiing all along, I said, what is the matter with these lodgers?
It's just, everything is so dead.
Nobody to ski with, nobody to talk to, just the people that run the lodge.
And everybody getting really grim, you know.
Of course, they had no business, you know.
You can imagine, your resort is falling, you know, no more income for them.
I didn't think in those business terms, but I thought at the time that there were a lot of Jewish people going skiing, and
You know, the fun, the laughing.
Maybe because I associated with the people leaving, you see.
Where's all the people?
You know, we had much more fun.
Is this the way it's going to be?
You know, kind of a drag.
I remember that kind of crossing my mind briefly.
You think it was because of the law of expelling the Jews?
Yeah, that's what I thought, you know.
Because where's everybody gone?
You know, that kind of stuff.
So the people you wrote to, you wrote to everybody at home.
You wrote to your folks.
You could keep in contact with.
Yes.
And the people who generally wrote back to you were these two girls, your parents, of course.
Yes.
Your brother Paul?
No.
Or Lottie?
Lottie might have made a footnote or something.
I don't think she wrote her separate letters.
We weren't on that boat.
But always a little note stuck with it.
Did they tell you about conditions at home, or it was just more chatty news?
No, just chatty news.
They didn't say things are going grim here?
No.
Uncle so-and-so is eating the grapes and we've been reduced to nothing like that.
It's nothing that...
I'm trying to find out how high your morale is in the camp and how isolated you are from events that are taking place.
I see.
I would say pretty isolated.
Maybe not me so much, but the rest of them that couldn't read as well.
Since you got the American newspaper.
Yeah, because I got the American newspaper.
I got to read all the color stories.
So you're building up an impression of how bad things are at home.
You're not getting it so much from letters from your family.
But you're reading the newspaper, among the few people who are, and you're building up a pretty grim feeling about what home is going to be like when you get back.
So when the final thing comes, that this is now falling into the Soviet zone, which it did, you weren't wrong.
You don't see much of an attraction there.
The letters are not that encouraging from your folks or from the lobby.
There isn't that much family connection.
that you really...
The last I remember was the Spears fighting.
I kept looking for the old man's name.
And the closest was the coal mines in Upper Silesia, which was very close.
And the fierce fighting that took place.
And the civilians that were fighting, they were fighting for their families.
There were really horror stories of them fighting.
And then between civilians and soldiers, which was unknown to me.
And the casualties, as we're always reporting.
Could I interject something here?
Could you talk a little longer?
I was looking for my town on maps and I could never find it.
So one of the first things that I did was to go to the library, and I got out every possible thing I could get, books, maps, everything.
In Waianae, Makah.
This town, one of the Polish ones with all the new names.
And he was frantic.
He was searching and searching this little library out in Waianae, Waianae.
And he found it in one of the maps.
It has no sweet nidsets.
Sweet nidsets, yeah.
You almost embraced that now.
Well, I thought that a lot of these towns were leveled.
So you had looked in libraries previously over the years.
Over the years you had?
Yeah.
I kept looking for that all the time, what ever happened.
Part of it was my anxiety, because I was always afraid to look.
It was that fear of what you might find.
So I was not a good looker.
She can calmly look.
I was too excited to look.
If you get too excited, you can't find anything.
Would you have looked while you were
working in Clinton's cafeteria, wandering into a library, or would you have... Not in those days.
Later on, I'd say, after I had a... Well, I would read the papers all the time.
I'm trying to think when I look.
And they would have maps in the paper, and that town was never in it.
Berkeley sounds like a likely place, too.
Would that be a place that you would be using the university library?
I was not that courageous to use these facilities.
I wished I could have.
I was afraid to ask directions.
I was too, you know, I wished I could have.
I'd love to have gone to Berkeley to school, but I just simply was afraid because
I never get close to authorities of any kind, county, city, county, state, federal.
I stay away from all the authoritative type.
And even to this day, Gene knows that.
I just hate it.
So I'm afraid that I have to fill out forms and ask questions that I can't answer.
I wanted to back up to fill in one gap in the escape itself.
I realized when we were through this that you never talked about food.
I got the sense of fear, the disappearance of the long run and the ride on the train and getting off the train and looking around, getting back on the train when the women looked at you and pointed.
Can you remember how you ate, when you ate, when did you realize you needed to eat?
I asked you the same thing.
You know, I wished I could remember.
I wish I wished.
The thing that I remember closely is that there was a huge rock in my stomach.
If you'd offered me that meal that we had last night, I doubt if I could have eaten it.
And I probably was about 20 or 30 pounds underweight.
I think you live on starvation or something.
I don't know how you survive.
But some, I'm sure, strangers offered me food.
And I'm sure I tried to get it, but I did not steal any.
I may have, let's see, in the desert where I was, the first 500 miles, there was nothing there to steal because there's no farms of any kind.
Eating a cactus.
Eating a cactus.
So it couldn't have been that.
And I think the first...
chance I had, I became a dishwasher.
When I saw the sign in the window, I simply became a dishwasher.
When you got to your first meeting.
Maybe just didn't eat, direct some water somewhere.
Yeah, direct maybe an orange or something, a fruit, or whatever.
But the first few days, just during the first 24 hours, 48 hours.
I doubt it, 48 hours.
72 hours.
I don't think I could have held any food.
Did you meet any hobos at that particular point?
Probably when the train stopped, there were men jumping out of it.
We would go down the train and there would be men jumping out, but you always had to be careful because they were immediately warned that there were going to be railroad digs.
I was immediately taught by these older men, like the older monkeys teaching the younger monkeys.
Be careful, the railroad guys are going to arrest you if you don't show yourself to open the gate.
Is that why when you said that you'd see some of the hobos jumping off out in the boonies, they would choose places?
Yeah, before they arrive at the yard, you must get off.
Not wait because they search the train when you pull in.
You have to get off outside of town and jump on outside of town.
But something else that we talked about in California, how our paths were kind of parallel.
We don't know if they ever converged or not.
And I remember in what had been a long about probably March or April of 1948 in California,
As part of my territory, I went to hobo camps along the Korea River.
Which river?
To interview people in hobo camps.
So I don't know.
I haven't seen firsthand what a hobo camp looks like.
I wonder.
Yeah, there's a little tin can with a coffee or the beans.
It's always on the fire.
So if you stumbled upon a hobo camp,
First, they just follow these guys, and they go to the next camp, and there'd be a pot of beans on a cup of coffee or something.
Enough to sustain you.
Enough to sustain you, they would give you.
But you did this life only for
A year or two?
Oh, less than that.
Probably just a few months until you get the first dishwasher job.
And then you get three square meals a day almost, you see.
And then you get a few meals ahead.
Yes.
And save a few bucks in whatever plan or ferments in your brain where you want to go.
And that would have happened.
That would have taken place.

After the few months, then one season with the Arkansas family up to Medford, then the log cutting, the calf incident with the splitter, down to the Mexican border, saw the darkness on the other side, and realized that the future was not there.
Having a dishwasher job in a waterfront cafe where all these workers come in, the dock workers come in.
Rowdy, raunchy, rowdy place.
Where was that?
In San Pedro.
That's where you were looking for the ships?
Yeah.
That was before you went north?
Yeah, before I went north.
These things are kind of like a bird landing and just checking it out.
How did you usually leave your jobs?
Did you just not show up the next day?
Not show up.
Make sure you got paid and that's it.
Right.
And generally, that was?
Cash.
Cash.
And just something alerted you, or you just decided it was time to move?
Fear, constant.
I don't think the first three or four years, you really live in constant fear.
Then later on, it goes partial fear.
And then it gets a little less, but it never completely disappears.
Did you think of writing to your folks
Where to?
Right.
Right.
During that period, you said that you really avoided reading the newspapers, that it was, what you were reading was too frightening.
I could see two areas that would be very frightening.
One was when you said the maps would be there and you weren't finding your village, and the devastation that you'd be reading about of your own country.
Fierce fighting.
And the other would be the revelation of the atrocities that were coming out of the concentration camps and so on.
Were those both stories that you, well, okay, the first area you expressed has upset you.
The second area, did you believe the stories of the atrocities?
I would say there's definitely aberrations that took place.
Did you believe them at the time or did you just shut it off?
Not the first, not right away.
At first I didn't because I left Germany that was entirely different from the one that occurred afterwards that changed in the actual war, the actual devastation.
There was hardly anything going on in my time, so I didn't see anything that may have taken place somewhere.
But you knew the Jews had been...
Yeah, most of them, as far as I know, were gone overseas, and whoever took them to foreign countries were going all over the world.
As far as I was told, they were allowed to leave, and they were, you know, so that was the point in time.
We had a few.
I remember we had a butcher, and I think we had a synagogue, and it was closed down.
I would say maybe 200 people out of a population of 20,000, maybe something like that.
I don't know.
I'm just guessing.
It was a small minority.
So that's another horror story that I knew would not end and would stay in Europe for the next 10,000 years.
But you didn't feel any responsibility for it.
You didn't have anything to do with it.
There was no reason why you had to.
That wouldn't have prevented you from
saying to somebody that you were German or you were German, I mean, it was really that you were concerned about being apprehended.
Yeah, I probably did, because I certainly didn't want to be associated with it.
Right, I see, I see.
Just like if you...
found out you worked for a crooked company or something, you could certainly disassociate yourself as quickly as you can.
So it made it a lot easier to amputate.
Yeah, it made it a lot easier.
I'm sorry, where did I start?
I was just looking down at my list because I didn't know if I had another question, and that's what made these rules that I pulled from going here.
Go ahead.
Just a small one.

When you talked about having this area way back and you've been quarantined, and you made a remark yesterday or the day before about your friends, you couldn't really keep in touch with them, but they could toss flowers out the window.
I pictured there a second floor window.
Were you up on the second story?
No, but I could climb up into my first apartment.
There was probably about seven feet off the ground.
Could you get up so that your face was over the window so you and they could talk?
Yeah, they could see me.
I could see, yeah.
You and they would talk.
Sometimes it was without me, so there was conversation.
They could stand there and we would talk, yeah.
That is something that I found very hard to relate to about one of his studies, was his own bedroom.
apparently was in the inner core of the house, and he told me, this is quite interesting, we had a period, we went to your parents' room.
Yeah, they gave me their room.
The room was this small, totally enclosed, no windows, no light kind of room, and no.
And he talks about having claustrophobia.
Claustrophobia, yeah.
It could have been.
My brother had the big room facing the street, Blue Brace Strasse,
Do you know how to spell that?
Yes, I have it on my postcard.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
So he had the largest room.
So you didn't share a room with your brothers and sister?
No.
When I got old enough, they gave me that.
It was almost a pass-through, like a large closet, had enough room for a bed.
And it was adjacent to my parents' bedroom and adjacent to the living room.
It would pass almost like a large walk-in closet.
Yeah, a large walk-in closet with no windows.
And Gina's always horrified.
She has to have a window.
She has to have air open.
The window has to be open.
And I said, I don't care.
Close that thing.
This was second floor, third floor?
No, nine feet up.
You could climb in it from the rear.
I climbed into it many times.
So the apartment was the first floor apartment?
The first floor apartment.
And then we had a basement.
And my father made near beer down there, and cabbage and pickles, and saw pickles, and stuff like that.
I miss what you're saying.
I was thinking, I could understand possibly why a child would be prone to pneumonia and numbness being in a .
And plus,
an unbalanced diet and a horrible climate, a pretty tough climate to live in.
You've got to be really, you know, A number one to survive there.
Did your friends come through often then, or was it once a week?
Did they every day on the way to school holler something to you?
No, it was once a week.
They kept in touch just to kind of cheer me up a little bit.
That was an all-boys school where you were going.
Yeah, all-boys, but the girls came.

Yeah, because we had, I'm trying to think of the name of that girls' school, which was the exact equivalent to what we had, and it was Ursula von Miller that Hans was so crazy about, and Maria Hoffman comes to mind, the other one, the doctor's daughter, went to first eventually, got quit, and...
I may have been one or two others, you know.
So I had friends, good friends in school that tried to cheer me up.
I got it from my cousin in Berlin.
She died of it.
I went into, I went to Berlin to cheer up her sister, and that was a really cute guest.
They looked Irish, freckles, and I was reading books that she had got, you know, picked up the virus from the books.
Also from that period, if you've already answered this in a letter or when I was out of the room, you don't need to answer, but I'm curious about your mom.
If you could describe your mom, who was she?
What was she like?
She was a very pretty lady and she was very proud of herself.
with a short aristocratic nose.
She thinks I have it, but I don't.
She hears much straighter and smaller.
And her laugh, she had a marvelous laughter.
She could get my father out of any mood that he was in by tickling his ears or blowing in his ears and laughing.
It got him to smile.
She had the loudest sneeze of anyone.
And I still have a similar one.
People always get startled when I sneeze.
I mean, she just blew out the windows when she sneezed.
And I do a similar number even to this day.
And she was always nursing me for something, hot and cold conferences for pneumonia or diphtheria.
And so she had a heck of a time with me.
And I guess it's awful hard to raise somebody.
And you can see it in a picture that I'm the thinnest of the bunch.
Very thin and very underweight and always, you know, skin and bones, they used to call me.
You could count the ribs, you know, and I have pictures even in this country of my skinny chest.
So I was always concerned with my...
I did my own reading.
She would always just supply me with whatever I wanted.
I had a little talk and chit chat and cheer me up.
But I had my own books.
I was more into reading than they were.
My parents get too busy to read.
They have to raise a family.
And my father's hobby was his pigeons, his Puffer pigeons, which he had in the back.
He built a cage over in the dump that we had our garbage dump.
And we spent many hours there.
Did your father ever take you on the train?
Oh, all the time.
Yeah.
So you went to Breslau, maybe, and you went to...
We'd meet him at the depot, sometimes pick him up, or I'd hang around the depot a lot to get a picture of him.
And read the magazines, have a magazine stand there just like they have here.
Read foreign, maybe foreign newspapers even.
Because I remember reading a lot about
England was running the world at that time.
So I remember reading what they said.
And at first, I remember reading the word common sense, which is a very popular expression in the English language, but not in German.
I don't think there's a word for it, even.
And I was always interested in finding out what common sense was.
The search for common sense.
The search for common sense.
I wanted to pursue that.
So do we all.
Because we had proverbs and things like that.
They contained maybe some common sense, but they also contained a lot of stuff that you didn't really need.
In fact, I just opened one up here.
That's the page.
This is from Christine Von of Sweden.
The first line I can't translate.
Maybe you can.
I forget what those words are.
Faden, what's a faden?
A pen, yes.
A pen, yes.
You cannot write with a borrowed pen?
Yes, you can't write long with a borrowed pen.
Man kann nicht lange.
You can't write with a borrowed pen for long.
You know, old wives tales and homilies.
You can't do it for long.
Yeah, and this one down here is kind of good.
Man soll seine Geheimnisse niemals unntig ausplaudern.
One should not blurb out your secrets unnecessarily.
Exactly that.
Right there.
And that's Christine of Sweden, the Queen of Sweden.
She was born on December 18th.
These are all people, everything relates to December 18th.
A horoscope, that's a good thing.
During your childhood, would you portray yourself as a very well-behaved child, or mischievous, or a combination?
Who were you?
I would say a combination.
I would get occasionally into trouble.
And how would they discipline you?
Oh, I did get a call to the principal's room one time, and it was really a pretty horrifying experience to be threatened with expulsion and things like that.
Yes, they really landed on me.
It was pretty frightening.
But most of the time, I was in the middle.
I was associated with the troublemaker, which was Hans Souvan.
He was my best friend, but I wasn't the actual troublemaker.
So you might say I was just near trouble all the time, but not necessarily in it.
Did your parents discipline you harshly?
Well, they, I think they laid down some pretty straight rules and they just, I always had the feeling they wanted just the best.

They wanted me to be, you know, better than they are and get a better education, get a better job, don't work so hard so you don't have to work so hard like my father does and, you know, get a nice easy job like we had a renter upstairs who worked for the city and
So your father owned the building?
Yeah, he owned the building.
I see, I see.
So he was the supervisor.
You had to solve the problems of the people who lived in the building, fix their plumbing, do things like that.
Yeah, he was very good at it.
Because he had been a superintendent on a construction before he, right after his war.
World War I, right?
Yeah, he had to show me pictures.
He had been a construction superintendent before.
He was very good at fixing anything in the building.
Yeah, that's right.
If things got really rough, I would crawl under the table.
If you couldn't get me out.
You mean, like, got really rough?

Well, if I was scolded for not doing this, then the other, whether my shoes were too dirty or I didn't do my homework or whatever, if they were landing on me, leaning on me too hard, asking me, I would simply...
We had a big, like that Spanish table.
We had a heavy wood table.
And so I crawled and was playing with that.
Were you hidden so they didn't know where you were?
Or was it just that they knew that you were hiding out?
At first, I thought they probably didn't know where I was because he was there.
Tablecloth.
Tablecloth hanging over it so I had my own little private hideout.
